Abongile and Sisipho still using letter trackers incorrectly.  I retrained.  Follow up on next visit.

They had kids that no longer attend school so their groups are not okay so we regrouped. I had 1 of their groups and did a full session while they were present and watching then after did admin so they can see it practically.

Overall sessions are going well. Books are consistently updated in-between sessions, session trackers and phonics trackers are  visible and up to date.  New LC is blending in well with the team. 

Living Ubuntu now has a total of 17 kids attending consistently, 7 kids are not attending anymore. The LCs now have 8 and 9 kids respectively. Because of low numbers Whitney can only do 4 sessions a day which is lower then the expected minimum of 5 sessions in ECDCs, Nomawethu on the other side has no reason not to do 5 sessions with the 1 extra kid she has, I have negotiated with the ECDC to make space in the center for at least 1 LC, the process of going across the street with kids is taking up time, in this winter time could even be a health issue for the kids. I still need to meet the principal to negotiate more space sothat both LCs can be stationed at Living Ubuntu, she was not available today.

Zikhona and Babalwa are settling very well. The minimum number of sessions are always met here at Sandwater. I observed Zikhona playing push buttons blending box, kids do not seem to get the concept, I explained the concept again to Zikhona after her session. I observed babalwa playing a game, she is abusing the play dough, I encouraged her to  utilize her games manual and incooporate  other games as well in her sessions.

Most learners are still doing vowels, most of them doing a & e. I've asked them to introduce more letters but also include the ones already learned during review and when playing games. Boniswa still needs a bit of support when it comes to conducting an effective session.

LCs still struggling to meet the daily target for sessions, they spend most of the time assisting in the classes that have no teachers. Session overall, Amyoli's session was solid, review was done as expected, story time was also great she used picture cards and her kids were engaged throughout. Xolelwa and Phumela need support when it comes to doing a proper review.
Did one minute assessments. Observed the new LC Tabita bakers she's doing fine but needs a bit of an assistance reviewing. Melumzi was absent he had an exam to write.

Same issue of kids not attending crèche anymore is happening here aswell, this results in LCs having less kids then usual thus effecting the number of daily sessions, Sanele has now 9 kids and natoline has 10. they strive for atleast 5 sessions but absenteeism aslo affects theire weekly sessions. I'm concerned by the quality of sessions, Living Ubuntu kids have slightly better 1min results then Bambino kids.

Learners are progressing well with their letters, few LCs were not tracking correctly and had learners/pairs being progressed at the same time focusing on the same letters. Review fairly done well. Blending done well, admin and session shows learners are blending on different reading levels. Games played are the same, rotation of the same games daily. Still need support when it comes to choosing appropriate games for learners on RL 3&4. Centre/Book shelves was a bit messy.

All admin is correct and up to date, phonics trackers are used accordingly. Sessions are going going well. I compared the January results with the phonics tracker infront of kids books, most of the kids know more sounds now. Spoke to the LCs and together agreed on a goal to at least average 10 sounds by June.

Review done well and blending going well, LC are teaching the skill correctly and kids seem to have grasped it. The two new LCs still needed a bit of support when it comes to letter tracking and following the correct teaching order. Although blending is done properly there was some confusion when it comes to knowing when do they start blending with learners, after we sat and talked they're clear. Also reiterated on them moving learners at the sametime and teaching the same letters even though they're moving at a different pace.

Kids in this center are progressing quit slow compared to kids in living ubuntu. I observed the quality of the sessions conducted.
